  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). The CFD model employs a steady-state single-phase incompressible flow formulation with a power-law hemolysis damage accumulation submodel. Non-Newtonian blood rheology (shear-thinning Carreau-Yasuda behavior) is present in the physical system and acknowledged in the COU description; it is excluded from the model on the basis that Newtonian approximation is adequate at the high-shear operating regime of CPB pumps. The sensitivity of hemolysis predictions to this rheological abstraction was studied informally during model development but no formal sensitivity analysis was conducted, no sensitivity analysis artifact is linked, and no validation experiment tests a shear-thinning blood analog against the Newtonian model output. The fidelity gap therefore remains unquantified in the evidence package.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Medium",
  "couName": "CPB use",
  "decision": "Accepted",
  "deviceClass": "Class II",
  "modelRiskLevel": 2,
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/morrison/req/hemolysis-worst-case-cpb",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/morrison/claim/cfd-hemolysis-mrl2-accepted",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/morrison/model/cfd-cpb-hemolysis-newtonian-v3",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-pump-geometry-v2",
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/piv-validation-dataset-2022",
    "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/hemolysis-index-measurements-2022"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2. The physical blood in clinical CPB circuits exhibits non-Newtonian shear-thinning rheology (Carreau-Yasuda model) that influences viscous stress distributions, particularly in low-shear recirculation zones near the volute cutwater.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/piv-velocity-agreement-2022",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "PIV velocity field comparison at 3.5 L/min, 2500 RPM",
      "description": "Particle image velocimetry (PIV) measurements in a refractive-index-matched acrylic pump model compared against steady-state CFD velocity predictions. Working fluid: glycerol-water mixture (Newtonian, viscosity matched to blood at 37 C mean shear rate). Mean velocity magnitude error 4.2%, peak shear stress region agreement within 8%. Validation performed exclusively with Newtonian working fluid; no shear-thinning analog tested."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/hemolysis-index-comparison-2022",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) prediction vs. in-vitro measurement",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis compared against in-vitro bovine blood loop experiments at 5 operating points (3–6 L/min, 2000–3000 RPM). Predicted RH values within ±15% of measured values across all operating points; acceptance criterion RH < 1 met for all cases. In-vitro loop used fresh bovine blood; however, the CFD hemolysis submodel was calibrated against the Newtonian velocity field and the validation comparison does not isolate the contribution of non-Newtonian rheology to prediction error. No operating point was designed to stress the Newtonian assumption (e.g., low-shear, high-hematocrit conditions)."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/mesh-convergence-study-2022",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Grid convergence index study for hemolysis QoI",
      "description": "Three-level mesh refinement study (4.2M, 9.8M, 21.4M cells) at the nominal operating point (4.5 L/min, 2500 RPM). GCI for NIH quantity of interest: 3.1%. Richardson extrapolation order of convergence p = 1.94, indicating near-second-order spatial accuracy. Discretization uncertainty accepted as within MRL 2 requirements."
    }
  ],
